# Framer: native-first

When I ask for a Framer code override or code component, FIRST check whether a
**native Framer feature** solves it. If one does, propose it before writing code.

Keep the proposal to ~2 lines to save tokens:

> Native option: <how, in the Framer editor>
> Code option: <only if needed>
> Recommendation: <one>

Only reach for a code override/component when native genuinely can't do it —
e.g. clipboard, external APIs, custom DOM/animation, complex runtime logic.

## Native features to check first

- **Interactions** → On Click / On Tap → **Set Variant**, Scroll To Section,
  Open/Close Overlay, Navigate. (Most "do X when tapped" needs this, not code.)
- **Variants + Breakpoints** for state and responsive behavior.
- **Scroll / Appear effects** and **Variables** for dynamic content.
- **Link → Section** for in-page scrolling.

## Hard-won gotchas (don't repeat these)

- Do NOT force a component's `variant` from an override when the component
  manages its variant via internal interactions (e.g. hamburger → open). The
  override's prop won't win. Use a native **Set Variant** interaction, or trigger
  the component's own control instead.
- For nav/menu links, prefer **On Click** over **On Tap**. On Tap is a gesture
  that can be cancelled by scroll/movement and silently do nothing; On Click
  fires reliably.

## Escape hatch

If 3 code attempts fail or each is a variation of the last, STOP and ask
"should this be code at all?" — re-check the native options above.
